```

This has a precedence issue due to short-circuit evaluation of `||`. Due to Rust's operator precedence, `&&` binds tighter than `||`, so this is:

```rust
if (tokens[0] == "find") || (tokens[0] == "sudo" && tokens.get(1) == Some(&"find")) {
```

That's actually correct! `==` has higher precedence than `&&`, and `&&` has higher precedence than `||`. So `a == b || c == d && e == f` parses as `(a == b) || ((c == d) && (e == f))`. In Rust, `==` has precedence 7, `&&` has 5, `||` has 4. So yes, this is correct.

